\begin_layout Section
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Optimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimization problem above has been solved using the IPOPT 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wachter2006implementation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 nonconvex solver, through the Yalmip 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lofberg2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 interface.
 The minimums found for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1,2,3,4$
\end_inset

 are shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:minvo_and_bernstein"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Both the Bernstein basis and the Lagrange basis are also shown for comparison.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One natural question to ask is whether the basis found consitutes a global
 minimizer for problem.
 To answer this problem, we can make use of Lasserre's moment method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "lasserre2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 By increasing the order of the moment relaxation, one can find tighter
 lower bounds of the original nonconvex polynomial optimization problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
From the view point of Problem 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In problem 1, the polynomial curve is given and we obtain the simplex we
 smallest volume.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, the simplex found for a given polynomial is shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:comparison2d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The simplex found using the Bernstein basis is also shown for comparison.
 Note how the MINVO basis is able to generate.
 In particular, it is guaranteed that the ratio between volume of the simplex
 generated using the MINVO basis and the volume of the simplex generated
 using the Bernstein basis is the following one:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{vol\left(S_{MINVO}\right)}{vol\left(S_{Berns}\right)}=\frac{abs\left(|\boldsymbol{A}_{Berns}|\right)}{abs\left(|\boldsymbol{A}_{MINVO}|\right)}\approx\frac{0.25}{0.3248}\approx0.7697
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that this ratio is independent of the polynomial given.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

, the simplexes found are showin in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:comparison3d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and the ratio is the following one:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{vol\left(S_{MINVO}\right)}{vol\left(S_{Berns}\right)}=\frac{abs\left(|\boldsymbol{A}_{Berns}|\right)}{abs\left(|\boldsymbol{A}_{MINVO}|\right)}\approx\frac{0.1406}{0.3319}\approx0.4236
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=4$
\end_inset

, the ratio is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{vol\left(S_{MINVO}\right)}{vol\left(S_{Berns}\right)}=\frac{|A_{Berns}|}{|A_{MINVO}|}\approx\frac{0.1406}{0.3319}\approx0.4236$
\end_inset


\end_layout

